		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://elijahtoten.com/?p=897</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[The hammer breathed in Snatch&#8217;s grip; it swayed back and forth and threatened to drop down onto Laura&#8217;s head at any second. The bright flashlight beam stayed focused on Snatch&#8217;s face, and the officer holding that flashlight continued barking orders. His words could have been in a different language. Snatch didn&#8217;t hear them. He focused [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>The hammer breathed in Snatch&#8217;s grip; it swayed back and forth and threatened to drop down onto Laura&#8217;s head at any second. The bright flashlight beam stayed focused on Snatch&#8217;s face, and the officer holding that flashlight continued barking orders.</p>
<p>His words could have been in a different language.</p>
<p>Snatch didn&#8217;t hear them.</p>
<p>He focused on Laura.<br />
<span id="more-897"></span><br />
Sweat pooled on his face and dripped from his low brow.</p>
<p>&#8220;You&#8217;re not Mother,&#8221; he whispered.</p>
<p>His headache asserted itself through his clouded state and crashed behind his eardrums. His brain felt as if it were in a spin cycle in the one unbalanced machine every laundromat in the world has. He vomited into his mouth and held it there.</p>
<p>The spice burned the inside of his mouth and made his teeth feel gritty, dirty, dry and wet at the same time. He blinked and tried to swallow the upchuck back down, where it belonged. His throat didn&#8217;t cooperate.</p>
<p>His throat clamped shut, firmly shook its head and told him no. He coughed and gagged at the same time.</p>
<p>The spicy mouthful of food and stomach acid spurted past his lips and up into his nose. His face felt like a fireball ripped through his nasal and sinus cavities.</p>
<p>He slung the hammer aside and held his huge hands above his head.</p>
<p>Sweat stung his eyes as he turned to look into the light.</p>
<p>&#8220;The hammer is down,&#8221; he murmured.</p>
<p>The officer barked another order, but its contents didn&#8217;t matter to Snatch.</p>
<p>&#8220;Now leave me the fuck alone,&#8221; Snatch said.</p>
<p>Other officers emerged from the shadows surrounding them in the forest, and Snatch finally became aware he was surrounded. Cops stood everywhere and more stepped to the meeting place in the forest with each second.</p>
<p>He counted them.</p>
<p>Ten.</p>
<p>Twelve.</p>
<p>Fifteen.</p>
<p>Standing all around him.</p>
<p>&#8220;Just leave me alone,&#8221; he said.</p>
<p>All the officers had their weapons drawn, pistols at the ready, but Snatch knew not a single one could actually pull the trigger. In their eager search, their hunt for this animal they now had surrounded, they&#8217;d created a dangerous situation.</p>
<p>Any flying bullet could easily strike an officer on the other side of the circle around Snatch.</p>
<p>Snatch saw this.</p>
<p>Through his headache and nausea, he saw this.</p>
<p>He stepped closer to the first officer, the one with the flashlight, quivering but still blinding.</p>
<p>The officer threatened to shoot.</p>
<p>Snatch barrelled into him and took him to the ground. He pushed up and tried to rush into the woods, but dizziness overtook him. He swayed in place, on one knee over the downed officer, and fell back, flat against the earth. He stared up into the treetops, past the canopy, into the black night sky.</p>
<p>The police officers weren&#8217;t afflicted in the same way he was. They didn&#8217;t struggle to overcome dizziness, confusion, headaches and voices. They didn&#8217;t flash in and out of reality. They weren&#8217;t focused on getting away no matter what. They didn&#8217;t want to just be left to themselves.</p>
<p>They were on him.</p>
<p>Like the animals they claimed him to be.</p>
<p>Snatch felt the first kick from one of the officers. A blow to the shoulder, that scraped up past his shoulder and chest and skidded over onto his neck.</p>
<p>The next one landed cleanly against his side.</p>
<p>Pain slammed through his nerves and crashed through his body up to his brain. The pain met with his headache and had coffee. After coffee, the pain took his headache into an alley and raped it. His headache had a baby.</p>
<p>A tearing, ripping pain born of the symphony of pain in his body slammed into him and asserted itself.</p>
<p>Snatch clamped his eyes shut and screamed out into the night.</p>
<p>The leaves in the forest shook and trembled.</p>
<p>The officers were the animals now and they fed off of of one another. Kick after kick landed on Snatch as they continued their flurried assault. Laura screamed for them to stop. <em>Just put cuffs on him</em>, she said, <em>and it will all be over. He needs help.</em></p>
<p>They didn&#8217;t stop.</p>
<p>A kick bounced like a baby on concrete off of Snatch&#8217;s temple.</p>
<p>Pain punched around in Snatch&#8217;s head. The night seemed to swallow him. He couldn&#8217;t catch his breath.</p>
<p>Through the pain, a voice reached through. A moment of nothingness cut his pain.</p>
<p>&#8220;Edgar,&#8221; the Reaper said, &#8220;look at me.&#8221;</p>
<p>Snatch turned his head and opened one eye to look past the legs kicking him. The legs seemed to move in slow motion, but he moved normally, and so did the rest of the world. Things distorted.</p>
<p>The sun shined in his eyes, but the night choked out the sun.</p>
<p>He blinked and focused on the Reaper, where the old farmer sat crouched just outside the circle of officers.</p>
<p>&#8220;You&#8217;re not real,&#8221; Snatch said. Blood dripped down into his open eye.</p>
<p>&#8220;Do you really want to debate this right now?&#8221; the Reaper questioned.</p>
<p>&#8220;Why are you here?&#8221;</p>
<p>&#8220;Have I ever told you how easy it is to break an ankle?&#8221; the Reaper asked. He motioned around Snatch, to all of the legs.</p>
<p>&#8220;I can&#8217;t win,&#8221; Snatch said.</p>
<p>&#8220;No,&#8221; the Reaper said, &#8220;but you can survive. You just need to fight back enough to break them out of this rage.&#8221;</p>
<p>&#8220;They&#8217;re just like Mother.&#8221;</p>
<p>The Reaper nodded. &#8220;Everyone has a little rage in them. Some people, like you, just have a different way of responding to it. Fight back right now.&#8221;</p>
<p>Snatch turned his head to look up at the night sky and felt his pain begin a slow return. Reality fought against the distortion his mind brought, and struggled to drag him back down to the dirt.</p>
<p>&#8220;We&#8217;re going to have a long, happy future together,&#8221; the Reaper said with a smile.</p>
<p>The headache returned. The pain returned. Blood dripped down Snatch&#8217;s brow and into his eyes. Still, he managed to reach and and grip one of the legs. Which one, he didn&#8217;t know, but one of the legs sat firmly in his grip.</p>
<p>He squeezed the leg in his grip and brought his other fist down, right on the ankle, where the foot met the leg. He felt his fist crush bone like a hammer.</p>
<p>Snatch heard a scream of pain, and this time it wasn&#8217;t his.</p>
<p>He grabbed another foot and twisted it in his grip. He felt the leg break or dislocate at the knee. He shoved the leg away.</p>
<p>Another scream of pain cut the night open.</p>
<p>Not his.</p>
<p>Hands reached down into the mix of legs. Another set of hands, and then another.</p>
<p>The officers rolled Snatch over, face down into the dirt and cuffed his hands behind him.</p>
<p>They dragged him to his feet.</p>
<p>Snatch swayed and would have fallen if a couple officers didn&#8217;t hold him up. He closed his eyes and tried to shut out the pain as they dragged him from the wonderful woods.</p>
<p>He stumbled along with the few officers that pulled him out of the woods and across the dead field dotted with hay bales.</p>
<p>The farmhouse blazed like a torch . Fire danced and fought with the darkness of the sky.</p>
<p>Snatch&#8217;s head cracked against the patrol car as police shoved him into the back seat of one of the many squad cars in the farmhouse driveway. He stared at the fire and for a moment, he saw a silhouette writhing in the fire.</p>
<p>Mother&#8217;s silhouette, a giant, flabby shape, struggled against the walls of flame around her.</p>
<p>&#8220;I hope it hurts,&#8221; Snatch murmured.</p>
<p>He leaned his head back and let blood drip from his teeth into the back of his throat. An officer leaned down and tapped the window to get Snatch&#8217;s attention.</p>
<p>&#8220;Hey, retard,&#8221; the officer said. &#8220;You&#8217;re going away for a long, long time, buddy. What kind of stupid name is Snatch, anyway?&#8221; The officer walked away and left the taunt hanging.</p>
<p>Snatch turned away and realized he wasn&#8217;t alone.</p>
<p>Next to him in the rear of the squad car, the Reaper sat calmly, with the seat belt buckled and his hands folded in his lap. Next to the Reaper, the dead Mouse sat, also buckled up and ready to go. They both turned to look at him.</p>
<p>Snatch laughed.</p>
<p>The sound grated on his own ears as the realization hit him. The officers couldn&#8217;t touch him. The real world couldn&#8217;t touch him. Mother couldn&#8217;t touch him.</p>
<p>Snatch&#8217;s laugh filled the car and blocked everything else out as he stared at the Reaper and the dead Mouse.</p>
<p>Nothing could touch him.</p>
<p>Snatch cut his laugh short and opened his mouth. His voice cracked and dragged itself past his bloody tongue, teeth and lips. His words carried the same sound as a bag of gravel grinding in slow-motion.</p>
<p>&#8220;All a sad boy needs is a friend and a pet.&#8221;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
]]></content:encoded>
