		<title>Snatch and the Hellish Hunt</title>
		<link>http://elijahtoten.com/2011/05/snatch-and-the-hellish-hunt/</link>
		<comments>http://elijahtoten.com/2011/05/snatch-and-the-hellish-hunt/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Sat, 07 May 2011 17:05:06 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Elijah Toten</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Edgar Snatch]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Fiction]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[serial]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[short story]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://elijahtoten.com/?p=890</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[The tree line loomed ahead as Snatch stumbled forward, on his way to the wonderful woods. The trees called to him as he felt the heat of the flaming farmhouse behind him. The flickering fire danced and threw wicked shadows against the dark tree line, shapes that Snatch thought he could see the Reaper and [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>The tree line loomed ahead as Snatch stumbled forward, on his way to the wonderful woods. The trees called to him as he felt the heat of the flaming farmhouse behind him. The flickering fire danced and threw wicked shadows against the dark tree line, shapes that Snatch thought he could see the Reaper and the dead mouse in.</p>
<p>Snatch&#8217;s senses stumbled less than he did. He could hear the sound of gravel crunching as more squad cars pulled into the farmhouse&#8217;s driveway and smell the sweat beading on each officer&#8217;s forehead. He saw the shadows swirling against the tree line as he stumbled toward the thin first line of trees.<br />
<span id="more-890"></span><br />
Snatch reached the tree line.</p>
<p>He turned and looked back toward the farmhouse engulfed in flames. The fire cracked and popped and the roof caved in.</p>
<p>The farmhouse exploded with a burst of flames as fire ate through to the propane, and steam billowed out from the fire as the old water heater&#8217;s safety valve overheated and opened up to let excess pressure out.</p>
<p>He looked past the flames, to the sea of blinking red and blues, the ocean of Crown Victorias in the farmhouse driveway. In reality, there were only six or seven squad cars, but Snatch saw hundreds, thousands, and every police officer there was ready to kill him.</p>
<p>He turned away from the officers and the lights and the fire and stumbled deeper into the woods. He heard the clicks and snaps as every officer unclipped the clasps on their guns.</p>
<p>Why couldn&#8217;t they just leave him alone?</p>
<p>He heard Laura deeper in the trees, somewhere in the frightening forest.</p>
<p>He realized the woods worried him when he stood in them, within the shadows thrown down to the dead dirt. Outside of the woods, he found them wonderful, welcoming, wanting. Inside, they were frightening. They scared him.</p>
<p>He searched around in the weeds growing around the thin trunks of scattered thin trees. He knew as he stumbled forward, he would find Laura somewhere, handcuffed to a tree where he&#8217;d left her.</p>
<p>And next to her, he&#8217;d find his sledgehammer.</p>
<p>Behind him, he heard the crashing of officers as they moved into the woods to look for him. Shouts and calls for him to stop did nothing to him. He moved on, through the trees, knowing he moved faster than them, even through his headache, and dizziness, and the stumbling and confusion.</p>
<p>These were his woods, his trees, his forest. This is where it all started for him. This is where he would go when Mother got drunk and kicked him out. He would spend the night among the trees, crying as he grew older and less loved.</p>
<p>Blood rushed behind his eardrums.</p>
<p>His heart pounded in his chest.</p>
<p>Sweat pooled in the folds at the back of his head and rolled down his neck and back. His greasy hair smelled so bad that his nostrils picked up the scent of it even past the scent of his sweat-fueled body odor.</p>
<p>He stopped and stood near a larger tree. He turned and surveyed the forest behind him. Officers were fanning out into the woods to cover more area.</p>
<p>They were hunting him.</p>
<p>Like an animal.</p>
<p>He pulled a slow, heavy breath through the thick Louisiana air. His senses fell into place and started to cooperate with him again. He fought his headache into submission and cleared his head.</p>
<p>To his right, an officer stalked through the woods. A young officer, frightened, sweating, gun trembling. He stood next to the tree where Snatch stood.</p>
<p>&#8220;I&#8217;m not an animal,&#8221; Snatch whispered.</p>
<p>He stepped around the tree and gripped the officer&#8217;s gun by the barrel and jerked it from the man&#8217;s grasp. In the same, fumbling motion he flung himself against the officer and sent him to the ground.</p>
<p>Snatch straddled the man and looked down at him.</p>
<p>&#8220;Why can&#8217;t you leave me alone?&#8221; he asked.</p>
<p>He glanced up from the downed officer and looked around. He saw flickering flashlights in the woods, but none too close.</p>
<p>He looked back down to the officer. The man struggled under Snatch&#8217;s weight and opened his mouth to call for help.</p>
<p>Snatch looked down at the gun, held by the barrel, in his hand. He slammed it cleanly against the officer&#8217;s forehead before he could make a sound.</p>
<p>&#8220;I&#8217;m not an animal,&#8221; Snatch said.</p>
<p>He stood up and dropped the gun.</p>
<p>His headache returned with force and ran down into his neck and shoulders. Sweat dripped from the tip of his nose. He burned up beneath his coveralls. He burned as if he stood at Hell&#8217;s gates.</p>
<p>He turned and swayed as the world moved under him and he looked up at the trees as they towered over him and taunted him. He licked his teeth, tasting the stale skin of plaque that covered them.</p>
<p>He needed to find Laura. He shook his head to clear his thoughts. He needed to do at least one thing right.</p>
<p>He could release Laura and show the hunters on his tail that he wasn&#8217;t the creature they thought they hunted.</p>
<p>He stumbled away from the downed officer and searched the trees for something identifiable, something he could gauge his location with. A vine, a strange mark on tree bark, anything he could use to help locate Laura.</p>
<p>As he searched, a random pass of a distant flashlight glinted off of something near the base of a tree in the distance. He rushed through the trees, toward the glint. He knew immediately what that little flash of light in the darkness was.</p>
<p>Handcuffs.</p>
<p>He approached the tree and slowed his gait. He sucked a breath into his chest and calmly approached the tree.</p>
<p>Laura was on the ground, arms still wrapped around the tree, with strips of blood on her wrists. He took a step closer to her and she turned to face him.</p>
<p>&#8220;Laura,&#8221; Snatch said. His hoarse, deep voice crawled past his tongue like a sack of rocks grinding together.</p>
<p>&#8220;I never should have gotten involved with you,&#8221; Laura said past her tears and trembling voice. &#8220;I should have gone with my instincts.&#8221;</p>
<p>&#8220;No,&#8221; Snatch said. He held up his hands to show they were empty. &#8220;I&#8217;m going to let you go.&#8221;</p>
<p>&#8220;Stop playing with me, Edgar. Just turn yourself in. I can hear the sirens. It sounds like the whole station is here. You&#8217;re done.&#8221;</p>
<p>&#8220;You don&#8217;t understand,&#8221; Snatch said.</p>
<p>&#8220;I understand,&#8221; Laura whispered. &#8220;I never should have gotten involved with you. Your last name is Snatch, for Christ&#8217;s sake. Snatch! What kind of name is that?&#8221;</p>
<p>Snatch took a step back and clenched his teeth.</p>
<p><em>Dirty, stinking Snatch</em>, he heard Mother say. <em>Dirty, stinking Snatch</em>.</p>
<p>His headache broke past his mindframe and blood rushed back into his head. A wave of heat rolled over his neck and head. He took a step back.</p>
<p>&#8220;Don&#8217;t say that,&#8221; he said.</p>
<p>&#8220;You&#8217;re going down,&#8221; Laura said. &#8220;Just give it up, Snatch.&#8221;</p>
<p><em>Snatch. You smell like one.</em> Snatch heard Mother&#8217;s words again.</p>
<p>&#8220;No,&#8221; Snatch said. He looked past Laura and spotted his sledgehammer on the ground.</p>
<p>&#8220;No?&#8221; Laura asked.</p>
<p>&#8220;No.&#8221;</p>
<p>Snatch stepped over Laura and leaned down to wrap both hands around his sledgehammer. Mother&#8217;s words ran through his head and he looked over at Laura as he lifted the sledgehammer above his head.</p>
<p>&#8220;No,&#8221; Laura said. &#8220;Don&#8217;t do it. Things will only get worse for you.&#8221;</p>
<p>He readied the sledgehammer and tensed his arms. He stared down at Laura and his lips twitched. Sweat rolled down his arms, into his armpits, and from his armpits, down his sides, to his waist. His coveralls were soaked through.</p>
<p>&#8220;I&#8217;m going to kill you, Mother.&#8221;</p>
<p>Laura&#8217;s eyes widened. &#8220;Edgar, no! I&#8217;m not your mother.&#8221;</p>
<p>&#8220;You never loved me, Mother.&#8221;</p>
<p>He stretched his body out and stepped one foot back to brace himself. He swung the sledgehammer high.</p>
<p>A bright flash of light momentarily blinded him.</p>
<p>&#8220;Drop the hammer!&#8221; the voice behind the light shouted.</p>
<p>Snatch looked into the light and could barely make out the shape of an officer, gun drawn and ready.</p>
<p>&#8220;Drop the hammer! I&#8217;ll put you down, I swear.&#8221;</p>
<p>Snatch looked down at Laura and his lips twitched and curled down into a sneer. The sledgehammer seemed to glow in the light.</p>
<p>The hammer felt so heavy in his calloused hands.</p>
<p>It wanted to crush Laura&#8217;s head.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
]]></content:encoded>
