		<description><![CDATA[I killed Mother. Snatch&#8217;s words ran through his head as he spoke them. They seemed unreal, twisted, warped, surreal. He gagged and fought back the rush of acid up his throat. His tongue convulsed in his mouth. “No,” he said, turning to look at the Reaper in his old farmer guise. “It&#8217;s not possible.” The [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><em>I killed Mother. </em></p>
<p>Snatch&#8217;s words ran through his head as he spoke them. They seemed unreal, twisted, warped, surreal. He gagged and fought back the rush of acid up his throat. His tongue convulsed in his mouth.</p>
<p>“No,” he said, turning to look at the Reaper in his old farmer guise. “It&#8217;s not possible.”<br />
<span id="more-886"></span><br />
The Reaper nodded. “Yes. It is possible.”</p>
<p>Snatch shook his head.</p>
<p>The Reaper stepped forward and pulled the piece of straw from between his dry, cracked lips. “Yes,” he said. He tossed the hay straw aside and unfastened the straps of his overalls.  He grinned and showed his yellow teeth.</p>
<p>As the Reaper dropped his overalls and stepped out of them, his body shape changed. He reached up to his face and peeled the skin back like a mask, starting at the chin and pulling up toward the top of his head. Underneath, it wasn&#8217;t bone, no skull. More skin.</p>
<p>Snatch stared in disbelief as the Reaper shed his clothing and skin.</p>
<p>The Reaper stripped his skin and clothing away, until Snatch realized he was staring at himself. Under all of the ripping skin and falling clothing, the Reaper looked exactly like him. Snatch squeezed his eyes closed and shook his head.</p>
<p>His headache returned with a nauseating force.</p>
<p>He opened his eyes.</p>
<p>The Reaper was gone, no longer standing in front of him. He pulled a breath through the thick hair hanging in the farmhouse and almost choked. The realization pooled behind his eyes. His bottom lip quivered and he licked each tooth, one at a time.</p>
<p>The Reaper was a figment of his imagination. The Reaper wasn&#8217;t real. He turned to look back at the decayed carcass under his floorboards.</p>
<p>Danielle.</p>
<p>Mother.</p>
<p>He stood and clenched his teeth. His hands trembled out in front of him as he tried to keep his body from swaying. He stood there in his room, swaying from side to side like a man on a tightwire, a tightrope act gone terribly awry. The balance required to keep his footing was just beyond his grasp.</p>
<p>His life fell apart around him.</p>
<p>He could feel his world crumbling like a broken tower of bricks and he fell. His body slammed against the wall and he squeezed his eyes closed to chase away the sound of rushing blood behind his eardrums.</p>
<p>His heart slammed in his chest and his stomach flipped and flopped like a toddler on a roller-coaster. He turned and saw the mouse, the dead mouse, on the floor.</p>
<p>It looked up at him with a dead grin.</p>
<p>“How&#8217;s it feel, Snatch?”</p>
<p>“What?” Snatch asked. He gripped his ears until his unclipped fingernails dug into the skin of his head and sent small lines of blood trickling down his flesh.</p>
<p>“How&#8217;s it feel to finally realize that it&#8217;s you? It&#8217;s all you. It&#8217;s always been you.” The mouse grinned, a yellow and decayed smile.</p>
<p>“You&#8217;re not real,” Snatch uttered.</p>
<p>“You&#8217;re right,” the mouse answered. “I&#8217;m in your head, and yet, here I am. On the floor talking to you. I&#8217;m a dead mouse! This is ridiculous!”</p>
<p>Snatch squeezed his eyes shut and shook his head from side to side with such force that his neck popped with each swing. He opened his eyes and the mouse was gone.</p>
<p>His headache rolled away into the recesses of his brain and the blood stopped rushing so loudly behind his eardrums. His world started to shift and become clear.</p>
<p>Under his floorboards he saw the truth. A dead woman. No strange gray hide textured like an elephant. Just the disgusting remnants of a corpse long dead.</p>
<p>It rolled back to him, in bits, in pieces.</p>
<p>He&#8217;d killed Mother some time ago, just to have some peace.</p>
<p>He&#8217;d gotten rid of the source of so much trauma in his life.</p>
<p>So he could live alone on his farm, alone with his thoughts, for what he&#8217;d hoped would be the rest of his life. Now, starting with the Sheriff, putting his nose where it didn&#8217;t belong, outsiders had started to pour in.</p>
<p>They just couldn&#8217;t let him live in peace.</p>
<p>Mother, the bitch, even dead, couldn&#8217;t let him live in peace. His mind would never let him live in peace.</p>
<p>In his few short moments of clarity, he realized his situation.</p>
<p>A police officer handcuffed to a tree in the forest. The entire station knew where she was. Other officers were likely on their way to the farmhouse now. They wouldn&#8217;t find the Sheriff&#8217;s body here, but they would find Mother.</p>
<p>He shook his head.</p>
<p>“That won&#8217;t happen,” he muttered.</p>
<p>His headache returned with the sound of triumphant trumpets in his ears. Like an elephant stomping his brain, pain rushed down his neck and into his spine.</p>
<p>He turned and headed out through the living room and into the kitchen. He snatched drawers out from their tracks and slung the doors to the cabinets open.</p>
<p>Matches.</p>
<p>He gripped the tiny box in his large, calloused hand and stumbled outside into the darkening day. He licked his teeth and searched the yard.</p>
<p>He walked around back and spotted what he was looking for.</p>
<p>Gasoline.</p>
<p>The large red container with the yellow nozzle stood as a stark opposite to the dead gray color of the lifeless grass. Snatch stumbled over to it and gripped the handle.</p>
<p>He shook the container side to side and heard the gasoline slosh against the sides of the weathered container.</p>
<p>“It&#8217;s enough,” he said. He unscrewed the nozzle and started splashing the farmhouse.</p>
<p>The ground fought against him and the world lurched from side to side in its half-hearted attempt at keeping him from completing his task, but it only took minutes, even through the confusion, the pounding of his heart, the panic rising in his throat, the sledgehammer of a headache against his temples and the roaring river of blood splashing its way behind his eyes and eardrums. He took several steps back from the house, carrying the gas can with him.</p>
<p>“Goodbye, Mother.”</p>
<p>Snatch struck a single match against the outside of the box, and dropped it into the open mouth of the gasoline can. Blue and orange flames licked around the mouth of the can, and Snatch slung it into the open door of the farmhouse.</p>
<p>He waited.</p>
<p>His heart pounded.</p>
<p>His breath caught in his throat and he swayed, almost fell, in place.</p>
<p>Any moment now.</p>
<p>The flames caught the gas fumes surrounding the house and roared to sudden life. Red and orange flames danced around the farmhouse. In the shapes of the flames as they grew higher, Snatch saw things.</p>
<p>He really saw them, he was sure. They weren&#8217;t in his head.</p>
<p>Burning down with his farmhouse, was the Reaper.</p>
<p>The dead Mouse.</p>
<p>And Danielle.</p>
<p>Mother.</p>
<p>He pulled his eyes away from the mesmerizing fire and saw lights flickering through the dancing flames. Red and blue. Several of them.</p>
<p>He recognized the appearance of the police lights.</p>
<p>“Come and get me,” he whispered.</p>
<p>He turned and stumbled toward the treeline.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
